Part 1

The company had no office in this state yet. There was only a corporate name that meant absolutely nothing to the locals, and a leather folder of licenses waiting to be argued over in the municipal offices. 

They had put him up wherever the local project team could arrange cheaply. It turned out to be a quiet, stone-walled farmhouse on a hillside outside the main town, surrounded by half-wild orchards and coffee plants, with the thick jungle pressing close against the far fence.

Vikram arrived alone in the back of the car, except for a driver whose name he had already forgotten, and a heavy leather suitcase that was not made for these unpaved dirt roads.

Ramanna kept the place. He was an old caretaker who carried a metal torch that flickered more than it lit, wore a white dhoti pressed into permanent wrinkles, and had a habit of calling every visitor "sir" in a dry tone that made the word sound like a question.

"Board members usually don't come to the site themselves," Ramanna said, unlocking the single guest room. "They send their junior officers."

"I am the junior," Vikram said, setting his bag on the wooden rack.

Ramanna looked at him properly for the first time, his dark eyes studying Vikram's tailored shirt and tired face. He decided something privately, nodded, and said nothing further about it.

---

The room smelled of the last rain, and the one before that, a damp, earthy scent that clung to the heavy wooden rafters. 

Vikram lay on the narrow cot, listening to the sounds that the city of Calcutta never let him hear. Some insect worked continuously at nothing in the corner, a dog somewhere on the hillside decided against barking at the last moment, and the old teak wood of the rafters creaked as it cooled for the night.

Sleep did not come easily anymore. It hadn't come easily since Ira, and since the daily board meetings had started depending on which way a state minister's mood tilted on a given morning.

He got up to get a glass of water near midnight and looked out the window. 

It was not close. Past the rows of coffee plants, at the very edge where the plantation gave up and the dark jungle properly began, a small flame moved. It was the kind of flame that only moves when someone is sitting beside it, keeping it alive.

A figure sat by the fire, motionless except for one arm rising and falling in a slow rhythm. Vikram couldn't place the movement from this distance; the figure was either throwing something into the fire or gathering something from the ashes.

He watched the flame for a long time, the glass of water cold in his hand, before returning to his bed.

---

At breakfast the next morning, Vikram sat on the stone verandah. He ate curd rice with a lime pickle sharp enough to clear his head faster than the chicory-scented coffee did.

Ramanna was scrubbing a copper vessel near the well. Vikram looked at him. "Who lights the fires past the plantation at night, Ramanna?"

The caretaker didn't look up from his work, his hands moving in circular motions. "Aghori Baba."

"Someone from the local village?"

"From nowhere, sir. From the jungle," Ramanna said. "He comes some nights, not others. Nobody invited him here, and nobody has told him to leave, so he stays." He shrugged, a gesture that closed the subject more firmly than any sentence could have.

"What does he do out there?" Vikram asked.

"Whatever Aghoris do." Ramanna finally looked up, wiping his wet hands on his dhoti. "If you want my advice, sir, don't go and ask him. He will tell you. That is the trouble with him. He always tells you."

Vikram laughed. It was the first time he had laughed in longer than he could place exactly. 

He didn't take the advice.

[End of Part 1]
